-
-                           Spring Boot Microservice
-                      Project Standards & Setup Guide
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-Maven :: GitLab CI :: SonarQube :: Java 17 :: VS Code
-                         Version 1.0   --   March 2026
-
-1. Project Overview
-This guide defines the complete engineering standards for the Spring Boot microservice project. Every configuration file referenced in this document is included in the project scaffold and is ready to use.
-
-ComponentTechnologyVersionRuntimeJava (Eclipse Temurin)17 LTSFrameworkSpring Boot3.4.xBuild ToolApache Maven3.9+CI/CDGitLab CILatestCode AnalysisSonarQubeLatestIDEVisual Studio CodeLatestContainerizationDocker (multi-stage)Latest2. Files Delivered
-The following configuration files are included in this setup:
-
-FilePurposepom.xmlMaven build with all plugins, profiles, and quality gates.gitlab-ci.yml6-stage CI/CD pipeline with parallel jobsconfig/checkstyle/checkstyle.xmlGoogle-based Checkstyle rules + complexity checksconfig/checkstyle/suppressions.xmlSuppressions for tests, DTOs, and generated codeconfig/spotbugs/exclude.xmlSpotBugs exclusions for Lombok and Spring patterns.editorconfigCross-IDE formatting consistency.vscode/settings.jsonVS Code workspace: formatter, Checkstyle, Maven.vscode/extensions.jsonRecommended VS Code extensions for the team.vscode/launch.jsonDebug/run configurations for Spring Bootlombok.configLombok restrictions and team standardsDockerfileMulti-stage, layered, non-root container buildsonar-project.propertiesSonarQube source/exclusion configArchitectureTest.javaArchUnit tests enforcing layer boundarieshooks/pre-commitGit hook for local format and lint checks.gitlab/merge_request_templates/Default.mdMR checklist templateapplication.ymlProduction-grade Spring Boot configuration.gitignoreStandard ignores for Java/Maven/IDE/VS Code3. Code Formatting & Style
-3.1 Google Java Format (Automated)
-All Java code is auto-formatted using Google Java Format via the fmt-maven-plugin. This eliminates formatting debates entirely  --  the formatter is the single source of truth.
- CI behavior: runs fmt:check to fail the build on violations
- Local fix: run ./mvnw fmt:format to auto-fix all files
- VS Code setup: the .vscode/settings.json configures Google Style via the Red Hat Java extension's built-in formatter. Format-on-save is enabled by default.
-
-3.2 VS Code Integration
-Three VS Code configuration files are committed to the repo so every team member gets an identical setup on first open:
- settings.json: configures Google Java Format via the Eclipse formatter profile URL, sets format-on-save, auto-organizes imports, integrates Checkstyle, and points Maven to the wrapper
- extensions.json: prompts all team members to install the same extensions: Red Hat Java, Spring Boot Tools, Checkstyle, SonarLint, GitLens, Docker, and GitLab Workflow
- launch.json: provides one-click Run/Debug configurations for the Spring Boot application and individual test files
-
-3.3 Checkstyle (Code Quality Rules)
-Checkstyle handles rules that a formatter cannot: naming conventions, complexity limits, Javadoc requirements, and import hygiene. Key rules enforced:
-
-CategoryRuleThresholdComplexityCyclomatic complexity per methodMax 12ComplexityMethod lengthMax 60 linesComplexityParameter countMax 7ComplexityBoolean expression complexityMax 4NamingClasses: PascalCase, Methods: camelCase -- NamingConstants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE -- NamingAbbreviations limited to 2 chars -- ImportsNo star imports, no unused imports -- Qualityequals/hashCode consistency -- QualityNo string literal equality (==) -- JavadocRequired on public classes and methods5+ linesFileMax file length500 lines
-In VS Code, the Checkstyle for Java extension (shengchen.vscode-checkstyle) is configured via settings.json to use the project's Checkstyle config. Violations appear as inline warnings in the editor in real time.
-
-3.4 EditorConfig
-The .editorconfig file ensures consistent whitespace, line endings (LF), and indentation across all editors. Java files use 2-space indentation to match Google Java Format.
-4. Static Analysis
-4.1 SpotBugs
-SpotBugs performs bytecode-level bug detection, catching issues like null dereference, resource leaks, infinite loops, and concurrency bugs. It runs at Max effort / Medium threshold and excludes Lombok-generated code and Spring controller patterns.
-
-4.2 SonarLint (Local Analysis in VS Code)
-The SonarLint extension (sonarsource.sonarlint-vscode) runs SonarQube rules locally in VS Code, giving developers instant feedback before they push. To enable connected mode (syncing rules from your SonarQube server), uncomment the sonarlint.connectedMode settings in .vscode/settings.json and provide your server URL and project key.
-
-4.3 Lombok Configuration
-Lombok is configured via lombok.config with these team standards:
- Banned: @val, @var, @SneakyThrows  --  these reduce readability and hide error handling
- Warning: experimental features and @UtilityClass
- Enabled: addLombokGeneratedAnnotation so JaCoCo and SonarQube skip Lombok-generated code
-5. Testing Strategy
-5.1 Test Classification
-TypeNaming PatternPluginRuns InUnit tests*Test.java, *Tests.javaSurefiretest phaseIntegration tests*IT.java, *IntegrationTest.javaFailsafeverify phaseArchitecture testsArchitectureTest.javaSurefiretest phase
-5.2 Code Coverage (JaCoCo)
- Line coverage: 80% minimum
- Branch coverage: 70% minimum
- Excluded: configuration classes, DTOs, entities, and the Application class
-
-5.3 Architecture Tests (ArchUnit)
-ArchUnit tests enforce architectural rules as executable code. Rules enforced:
- Layer dependencies: Controller --> Service --> Repository (no reverse access)
- Controllers must not call repositories directly
- Services must not depend on HTTP servlet classes
- No field injection (@Autowired)  --  constructor injection only
- Naming conventions: *Controller, *Service/*ServiceImpl, *Repository
-6. CI/CD Pipeline (GitLab CI)
-The pipeline has 6 stages. Validate and test jobs run in parallel within their stage for faster feedback. The pipeline uses the Eclipse Temurin Java 17 Docker image.
-
-StageJobsPurposevalidateformat, checkstyle, enforcerCode style, naming rules, build environmentbuildcompileCompile sources and annotation processorstestunit, integration, spotbugsRun tests, collect coverage, static bugsanalyzesonarqubeSonarQube analysis with quality gate waitpackagejar, dockerBuild artifact and container imagedeploystaging, productionManual deployment to environments
-6.1 Pipeline Triggers
- Merge requests: validate --> build --> test --> analyze (SonarQube MR decoration)
- Default branch push: full pipeline including package stage
- Tags: full pipeline including production deploy (manual gate)
-
-6.2 SonarQube Integration
-SonarQube receives reports from three sources for a unified quality view:
- JaCoCo: code coverage XML report
- Checkstyle: style violation XML report
- SpotBugs: bug detection XML report
-
-Setup required in GitLab CI/CD Variables (Settings --> CI/CD --> Variables):
- SONAR_HOST_URL  --  your SonarQube server URL
- SONAR_TOKEN  --  project authentication token (masked)
-7. Docker Best Practices
-The Dockerfile follows production best practices using Eclipse Temurin 17 JRE:
- Multi-stage build: extracts Spring Boot layers for optimal Docker layer caching
- Non-root user: runs as appuser for security
- JVM tuning: container-aware memory settings (-XX:+UseContainerSupport, 75% RAM cap)
- Health check: built-in Docker HEALTHCHECK hitting the actuator liveness endpoint
- Minimal base: Eclipse Temurin JRE-only image (not full JDK)
-8. Maven Build Profiles
-ProfileCommandUse CaseDefault./mvnw verifyFull build with all checks and testsCI./mvnw verify -PciCI-specific settings (strict format check)Fast./mvnw verify -PfastSkip all checks and tests for rapid iteration9. Developer Workflow
-9.1 One-Time Setup
- Install Java 17 (Eclipse Temurin recommended)
- Install VS Code and open the project  --  accept all recommended extensions when prompted
- Install the pre-commit hook: git config core.hooksPath hooks
- Verify the build: ./mvnw verify
-
-9.2 Key VS Code Extensions to Accept
-When VS Code opens the project for the first time, it will prompt to install recommended extensions from .vscode/extensions.json. The critical ones are:
- Red Hat Java + Spring Boot Tools: language support, IntelliSense, and Spring-aware navigation
- Checkstyle for Java: inline violations as you type, using the project's config
- SonarLint: local SonarQube rule analysis before pushing
- GitLab Workflow: view MR status and pipeline results from VS Code
-
-9.3 Daily Workflow
- Create a feature branch from main
- Write code  --  VS Code formats on save and shows Checkstyle/SonarLint violations inline
- The pre-commit hook catches anything missed before it reaches CI
- Push and create a merge request  --  the CI pipeline validates everything
- Address any SonarQube findings from the MR decoration
- Merge after review and green pipeline
-10. Modern Best Practices (Java 17)
-10.1 Code Practices
- Records for DTOs: use Java records for simple immutable data carriers where Lombok is overkill
- Sealed classes: use sealed types for domain hierarchies (Java 17 feature) to restrict inheritance
- Pattern matching for instanceof: use instanceof pattern matching to avoid explicit casts (Java 16+)
- Text blocks: use text blocks (""") for multi-line strings like SQL, JSON templates
- Constructor injection: enforced by ArchUnit  --  use @RequiredArgsConstructor with Lombok
-
-10.2 API Practices
- Problem Details (RFC 9457): use Spring's ProblemDetail for standardized error responses
- Input validation: use Jakarta Validation (@Valid) on all request DTOs
- API versioning: version via URI path (/api/v1/...) for simplicity
- Pagination: use Spring Data's Pageable with sensible defaults
-
-10.3 Observability
- Structured logging: use SLF4J with MDC for trace IDs (configured in application.yml)
- Metrics: Micrometer + Prometheus endpoint exposed at /actuator/prometheus
- Distributed tracing: OpenTelemetry bridge included for trace propagation
- Health checks: Kubernetes liveness/readiness probes enabled via actuator
-
-10.4 Security Defaults
- Docker container runs as non-root user
- open-in-view: false prevents the lazy-loading anti-pattern and accidental N+1 queries
- Graceful shutdown enabled for zero-downtime deployments
- Pre-commit hook scans for accidentally committed secrets
